<section id="using-vm-server" xreflabel="Installing a VM Server">
	<title>Installing a VM Server</title>

<para>
A VM Server is machine that can house virtual frontend appliances.
It is required to build a VM Server if you wish to build virtual clusters.
</para>

<para>
A VM Server takes the place of a traditional physical frontend, that is,
the first machine you'll build in your cluster is a VM Server rather than
a frontend.
</para>

<para>
To build a VM Server, boot the machine with the Kernel/Boot CD and at
the <computeroutput>boot:</computeroutput> prompt type:
</para>

<screen>
build appliance=vm-server
</screen>

<para>
The remainder of installation is the same as building a traditional physical
frontend.
Follow the procedure
<ulink url="/roll-documentation/base/&document_version;/install-frontend.html">
Install and Configure Your Frontend</ulink> starting at Step 3.
</para>

<para>
After you build the VM Server, you'll need to install VM Containers (see
the next section).
</para>

</section>

